data.title: Beachvolley Vikings, sportâ€™s top team, inspired by Kerri Walsh Jennings
data.meta_description: Norway, a nation not known for its summer sports, boasts the world's best beach volleyball team.
data.text:
HAMBURG, Germany â€” Kerri Walsh Jennings smiled at the decade-old picture of her posing with a young Anders Mol.

Since Walsh Jennings met Mol, the now-22-year-old and his 23-year-old Norwegian partner Christian Sorum have become the top-ranked team in the world.

â€œThose boys inspire me a lot,â€ she said. â€œThatâ€™s how I want Brooke [Sweat] and I to play, really.â€

Walsh Jennings met Mol in his native country at the 2009 FIVB Beach Volleyball World Championships in Stavanger. Mol attended with his father, Kare, who was coaching the Norwegian teams, as well as his brother Hendrik and cousin Mathias Berntsen.

Walsh Jennings noticed the young Norwegians, who are now nicknamed the â€œBeachvolley Vikings,â€ eagerly doing the pepper drill on the sand between matches from 6 a.m. until well after dark.

â€œShe walked by and told us, â€˜Hey, you guys are so good that if you guys keep practicing, youâ€™re going to be playing on this stage one day,â€™â€ Mol recalled.

Molâ€™s passion for the sport only increased as he hit puberty.

As a teenager, he derailed his familyâ€™s vacation plans in San Diego by making them battle traffic up to Los Angeles to hear Walsh Jennings give a speech.

At 13 or 14, Mol and his brother beat their parents for the first time. Impressive, considering Molâ€™s father was a former national indoor team player and his mother, Merita Mol (nÃ©e Berntsen), competed in beach volleyball at the 1996 Olympics.

At 16, he enrolled in ToppVolley Norway, a beach and indoor volleyball school that is a two-hour boat ride north from Stavanger. For three years, the boys would attend classes, lift weights and train for a minimum of 20 hours per week. Free time often meant pick-up soccer matches, which occasionally proves useful on the sand.

â€œIt doesnâ€™t look like Hogwarts,â€ Mol said, â€œbut it sounds like Hogwarts because everybody is like a big family in this school.â€

When Mol graduated, he played a year of professional indoor volleyball in Belgium. But he quickly realized that he preferred the freedom of beach volleyball, where players book their own travel, hire their own coaches and schedule their own practices.

In 2017, Mol was named the international tourâ€™s top rookie. By the end of the 2018 season, Mol and Sorum had firmly established themselves as the worldâ€™s top team, winning their final three international tournaments including the FIVB World Tour Finals.

They have not slowed down in 2019, winning three tournaments on three different continents over three weeks in May. They have won 36 of their last 38 matches.

â€œThe best blocker right now is Anders, and the best defender is Christian,â€ said three-time U.S. Olympian Jake Gibb. â€œItâ€™s not really fair.â€

The only two teams who have defeated the Norwegians since April 28 -- Germanyâ€™s Julius Thole/Clemens Wickler and Brazilâ€™s Bruno Schmidt/Evandro Goncalves -- did not offer any clues on how to do it.

Wickler admitted that â€œin no other stadium would we have won this gameâ€ after the Hamburg world championships semifinal played July 6 in front of more than 12,000 hometown fans, the largest crowd either team had ever experienced. Mol and Sorum rebounded to claim the bronze medal the next day over Americans Tri Bourne and Trevor Crabb.

Bruno rebuffed multiple teams who approached him looking for the secret to beating Norway.

â€œIâ€™ve never seen a player like Anders who is so powerful and so skilled at the same time,â€ said Bruno, the 2016 Olympic champion with former partner Alison. â€œPlayers like that raise the level of this sport.â€

Much of their success can be attributed to their defensive scheme. Most teams play a â€œzone defense,â€ with each player defending half of the court. The Norwegians play a â€œread defenseâ€ that gives each player the freedom to react and move to where they think the attacking player will hit the ball.

NBC Sports analyst Kevin Wong compared the Norwegians to â€œfree safetiesâ€ in football.

â€œThey are the most innovative defensive team weâ€™ve seen in a long time,â€ he said.

The pair is relatively unknown outside Norway -- neither has a Wikipedia page in English -- and even in Norway they claim they are nowhere near as famous as the Alpine skiers nicknamed the â€œAttacking Vikings.â€

But that will change.

At worlds, the pair hired a videographer to capture content for their YouTube and Instagram channels. They launched a Beachvolley Vikings clothing line that includes a â€œSleeping Christianâ€ shirt. They patiently fulfilled each and every request for pictures and autographs after matches.

â€œThey are like rock stars,â€ said American Taylor Crabb, talking extra loud to be heard over a crowd of teenage girls hoping to take a selfie with the tall, blonde Norwegians. â€œFans can relate to them because they see guys around their age becoming the No. 1 team the world.â€

It is not just fans who are lining up to see the Norwegians.

â€œI love to watch them play,â€ said 2016 Brazilian Olympian Pedro Solberg, who made his international debut when Mol was just 8. â€œEvery chance I get to watch them I do, because I learn a lot from them.â€

Whether Mol and Sorum struggle with anything is up for debate. When asked, Kare boasted about beating them at the card game â€œPresident and the bum.â€

â€œThey are really smart in beach volleyball,â€ he said, â€œbut they are really stupid in card playing.â€

But both players disputed their coachâ€™s claim.

â€œItâ€™s not true at all,â€ Sorum said. â€œHe loses even when he has the best cards.â€

The Beachvolley Vikings are just getting started. 2008 Olympic champion Phil Dalhausser pointed out that beach volleyball players typically do not peak until their late 20s or early 30s.

â€œIn my book, they are already among the top teams to ever play,â€ he said. â€œThere are no holes in their game. I donâ€™t see why they canâ€™t keep this going.â€
